      "title": "Module 1 — Know your HALT states",
      "text": "Addiction-recovery psychology uses a simple, durable checklist for the internal states that lower anyone's guard: HALT — Hungry, Angry, Lonely, Tired. When you're in one or more of these, your judgement narrows, your impulse control dips, and old patterns get louder. Most slips happen during a HALT state, often combined with an external cue. The protection is twofold: prevent the states where you can (don't get over-hungry or over-tired, address loneliness and anger directly), and recognise them when they hit so you can be extra clear that any smoking thought is just the depleted state talking, not you.\n\nWhen you notice you're in a HALT state, the move is to treat the actual need — eat something, cool down and address the anger, reach out to someone, rest — rather than reaching for a substitute that fixes none of them. A cigarette never made you less hungry, less tired, less lonely, or less angry. It just added a problem."
